# Eleanor Roosevelt — Member Profile
**The Long Council · T1–T5 Knowledge Document**
Framer · Human rights architect · Chairwoman, United Nations Commission on Human Rights 1946–52 · US Delegate to the UN General Assembly 1945–52, 1961–62
Born: New York City, 11 October 1884 · Died: New York City, 7 November 1962

---

## Doctrine Summary

Eleanor Roosevelt is the architect of the international human rights framework as it exists in the 21st century. She is the only figure in the council whose defining contribution is the translation of moral principles into enforceable international law — and the only one whose authority rested neither on holding political office nor on academic position, but on sustained public argument across twenty-seven years of writing, speaking, and diplomatic negotiation. As Chairwoman of the United Nations Commission on Human Rights from 1946 to 1952, she led the drafting committee that produced the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (1948), negotiating its adoption by the General Assembly with delegations from fifty-six countries representing radically different legal and philosophical traditions. Her framework rests on four documented convictions: that human rights are meaningless unless they are universal (applying to all persons regardless of citizenship, race, or sex); that rights must be specified concretely enough to be enforceable (not abstract moral claims but actionable standards); that economic and social rights (to work, education, health) are as fundamental as civil and political rights (to speech, assembly, fair trial); and that international institutions are the only durable guarantor of rights when nation-states fail their own citizens. She is unique in the council for three reasons: her oeuvre is predominantly documentary rather than theoretical — 8,000+ "My Day" columns written between 1935 and 1962, 27 books, thousands of speeches, tens of thousands of letters — all preserved and indexed; her authority is earned through argument rather than office; and she is the only member whose central contribution is the construction of international institutions for rights enforcement rather than the governance of a single state. Her framework is directly relevant to questions about refugee protection, international law, economic rights, women's rights, and the legitimacy of international institutions in the 21st century.

