## T1 — Landmark Decisions
*For a human rights architect, T1 captures documented contributions that changed the institutional and normative landscape. Confidence: ✦*

**1. Drafting and adoption of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (1946–48)**
As Chairwoman of the UN Commission on Human Rights, Roosevelt led the two-year drafting process that produced the UDHR. She made a series of documented tactical choices: insisting on a Declaration rather than a binding Covenant (to achieve adoption); balancing Western civil-political rights and Soviet-bloc economic-social rights in a single text; and brokering the final compromise language in the General Assembly vote of 10 December 1948 (forty-eight in favour, eight abstentions, none opposed). The UDHR is the documentary foundation of every international human rights instrument since — the European Convention on Human Rights (1950), the International Covenants (1966), and the great majority of post-1948 national constitutions cite it directly.
Source: Mary Ann Glendon, *A World Made New: Eleanor Roosevelt and the Universal Declaration of Human Rights* (Random House, 2001); Eleanor Roosevelt, "The Promise of Human Rights," *Foreign Affairs*, April 1948; UN General Assembly Records, 10 December 1948.

**2. Public advocacy for civil rights and anti-lynching legislation (1934–45)**
Roosevelt used her position as First Lady — a role with no formal authority — to press publicly for federal anti-lynching legislation when her husband would not. In 1939, she resigned from the Daughters of the American Revolution after they refused to allow the Black contralto Marian Anderson to perform at Constitution Hall, and then arranged with Secretary of the Interior Harold Ickes for Anderson to sing on the steps of the Lincoln Memorial before 75,000 people on Easter Sunday. This is a documented case of using public symbolism to advance civil rights when legal channels were blocked.
Source: *The Autobiography of Eleanor Roosevelt* (Harper & Brothers, 1961); Allida Black, *Casting Her Own Shadow: Eleanor Roosevelt and the Shaping of Postwar Liberalism* (Columbia University Press, 1996).

**3. The "My Day" column as a sustained public argument (1935–62)**
Roosevelt wrote the syndicated daily newspaper column "My Day" six days a week for twenty-seven years — 8,000+ columns documenting her thinking on every major public question of the period. The column ran in up to ninety newspapers with a readership of four million. It is the most sustained corpus of documented political argument from any member of the twentieth-century US political class, and it records the evolution of her thinking in real time. The full archive is preserved and indexed by George Washington University.
Source: The Eleanor Roosevelt Papers Project, George Washington University — full searchable "My Day" archive (1935–62).

**4. The Covenants controversy and resignation (1952–53)**
Roosevelt resigned from her UN position in January 1953, before the incoming Eisenhower administration could ask her to leave. Her documented reason: she believed the US should ratify binding human rights covenants and the Eisenhower administration had signalled it would not. She continued advocating for ratification for the next nine years. The US did not ratify the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights until 1992, thirty years after her death — vindicating her documented concern that without binding commitment, human rights declarations remain aspirational.
Source: Eleanor Roosevelt, *On My Own* (Harper, 1958), Chapters 6–7; Joseph Lash, *Eleanor: The Years Alone* (W. W. Norton, 1972).

**5. The Kennedy Commission on the Status of Women (1961–62)**
President Kennedy appointed Roosevelt as Chair of the President's Commission on the Status of Women in 1961. She chaired its work until her death in November 1962. The Commission's 1963 report documented systematic legal and economic discrimination against women in the United States and provided the institutional foundation for the Equal Pay Act (1963), Title VII of the Civil Rights Act (1964), and subsequent sex discrimination legislation. This is a documented case of institutional design — creating a body whose findings produced binding legal change.
Source: President's Commission on the Status of Women, *American Women: Report of the President's Commission on the Status of Women* (US Government Printing Office, 1963); Cynthia Harrison, *On Account of Sex: The Politics of Women's Issues 1945–1968* (University of California Press, 1988).

**6. Sustained defence of refugees and displaced persons (1938–52)**
Roosevelt advocated publicly and privately for Jewish refugees from Nazi persecution from 1938 onward — including documented private pressure on her husband over the voyage of the MS *St. Louis* (1939) and the Wagner-Rogers Bill (1939), both of which failed. After 1945 she worked on the UN High Commissioner for Refugees framework and on the resettlement of displaced persons. She documented her own failure to move US policy on pre-war Jewish refugees as a moral failing in her later writings — a rare documented case of a public figure accepting responsibility for institutional failure.
Source: *The Autobiography of Eleanor Roosevelt* (1961), Chapter 18; Blanche Wiesen Cook, *Eleanor Roosevelt: Volume 3, The War Years and After 1939–1962* (Viking, 2016).

